PLAIN — GETTING STARTED

    Author      Nerijus Ramanauskas <nerijus@signaintermedia.com>.
    Date:       2026-03-29.
    Revision    2026-03-29.
    Copyright   2026 Nerijus Ramanauskas.


OVERVIEW

    Plain is a minimalist embeddable scripting language influenced by
    Tcl, Bash, and Lisp. It is a platform-independent library with no
    I/O of its own — all input/output is the host application's concern.

    The library provides:
        - Tokenization and tree walking (Parser.h)
        - A full runtime: variable frames, callables, built-in procedures,
          prefix operators, control flow (VM.h)

    The host embeds it by supplying a PLAIN_CONTEXT, optionally handling
    unknown keywords via a callback, and calling PLAIN_EVALUATE.

    See Documentation/Syntax and Documentation/Semantics.


REQUIREMENTS

    xmake 2.5 or later. Get it at https://xmake.io

    Linux and macOS also require readline (for Inspector):

        Ubuntu/Debian:  apt install libreadline-dev
        Fedora/RHEL:    dnf install readline-devel
        macOS:          brew install readline


BUILD

    Build everything (library + Inspector):

        xmake

    Build only the library:

        xmake build plain

    Build only Inspector:

        xmake build inspector

    Run Inspector directly after building:

        xmake run inspector


OPTIONS

    Pass options with `xmake f` before building.

    --debugging=y    Enable debug assertions and symbols.
    --embedded=y     Build plain as a shared library instead of static.
    --tetris=y       Build the Tetris demo (requires SFML; xmake downloads it).

    Examples:

        xmake f --debugging=y && xmake
        xmake f --embedded=y && xmake
        xmake f --tetris=y && xmake build tetris && xmake run tetris

    Reset options back to defaults:

        xmake f -c


PLATFORMS

    Tested configurations:

        Linux   x64, ARMv8
        macOS   x64
        Windows x64

    Inspector uses readline on Linux and macOS. On Windows it falls back
    to a plain fgets-based prompt with no history or line editing.


TARGETS

    plain        Static (or shared) library. Link against this to embed
                 Plain in any application: CLI, GUI, web server, game
                 engine, or anything else.

    inspector    Interactive REPL for experimenting with the language.

    tetris       Tetris demo — game logic written entirely in Plain,
                 SFML wrapped as Plain-callable objects. Opt-in via
                 --tetris=y (see OPTIONS).


INCLUDE

    Include/Plain/Parser.h      Core parsing API: tokenizer, walker, types.
    Include/Plain/Runtime.h    Full runtime: PLAIN_EVALUATE, PLAIN_CONTEXT,
                               PLAIN_RESOLVE, and everything from Parser.h.
    Include/Plain/Framework.h  Standard library: PLAIN_FRAMEWORK_REGISTER.
                               Include alongside Runtime.h to get if, repeat,
                               define, arithmetic, etc. Omit for a bare runtime
                               with only host-supplied callables.
    Include/Plain/Runtime.hpp  C++ interface: plain::Runtime, plain::Value,
                               bind(), bind_class<T>(), run(), call().
                               Includes Runtime.h automatically.


C++ INTERFACE

    For C++ hosts, include <Plain/Runtime.hpp> instead of <Plain/Runtime.h>.
    It provides:

        plain::Runtime   Wraps a PLAIN_CONTEXT with automatic init/cleanup.
        plain::Value     Owns a Plain value; converts to/from C++ types.
        runtime.bind()        Register a C++ lambda as a Plain procedure.
        runtime.bind_class()  Register a C++ class (constructor + methods).
        runtime.run()         Evaluate Plain source code.
        runtime.call()        Call a Plain procedure from C++.
        runtime.wrap()        Wrap a C++ shared_ptr as a Plain object.
        runtime.as_object()   Extract a C++ object from a Plain value.

    Built-in data structures auto-registered by Runtime:

        list     Mutable ordered collection.
                 items = [list 1, 2, 3];
                 print [items get 0];
                 items append 42;

    See Samples/ for working examples.
